#: resources/locales/en/methodology_simple.md:1
msgid "CO₂ budget calculation"
msgstr ""

#: resources/locales/en/methodology_simple.md:3
msgid ""
"A CO₂ budget shows how much carbon dioxide (CO₂) a city or country is still "
"permitted to emit in order to limit global warming to a specific "
"temperature. The Paris Agreement, adopted in 2015, is particularly important "
"in this regard. Under this agreement, many countries have committed to "
"keeping global warming well below 2 °C compared to pre-industrial levels. "
"Where possible, warming should even be limited to 1.5 °C."
msgstr ""

#: resources/locales/en/methodology_simple.md:10
msgid ""
"To ensure these targets are met, every country and every city has a "
"responsibility. This is why the selected city must also reduce its CO₂ "
"emissions. To this end, a calculation is made of how much CO₂ the selected "
"city is still permitted to emit without further worsening global warming. "
"This amount is called the CO₂ budget."
msgstr ""

#: resources/locales/en/methodology_simple.md:16
msgid ""
"The global budget specifies how much CO₂ may still be emitted worldwide in "
"order to stay within the limit of 1.5 °C or 2 °C of global warming. To "
"calculate the CO₂ budget of the selected city, we take the global CO₂ budget "
"and allocate it according to the city's population share of the world "
"population. This gives us the CO₂ budget that would be fair for the selected "
"city."
msgstr ""

#: resources/locales/en/methodology_simple.md:22
msgid ""
"The cities for which the CO₂ budget tool is available measure their "
"emissions according to a specific standard, the [BISKO framework]{1}. This "
"estimate shows how much CO₂ is generated in the selected city. However, "
"BISKO only records emissions that arise directly within the city, such as "
"those from cars or heating systems. It does not account for emissions caused "
"by residents of the city outside the city limits, for example through air "
"travel or products sourced from other regions. As a result, the BISKO data "
"covers only approximately 64 % of the total CO₂ emissions actually caused by "
"residents of the selected city. The remaining 36 % are emissions generated "
"outside the city limits that must nevertheless be attributed to the city's "
"population. The budget displayed shows only the 64 % of emissions according "
"to the BISKO standard."
msgstr ""
